(Match 146)  4th June 1929  (Friendly match)
HOLLAND - SCOTLAND  0-2  (0-2)
Referee:   Otto Ohlsson (Sweden)
Crowd:     24.000, Olympisch Stadion, Amsterdam
Goals:     0-1 Fleming (30), 0-2 Rankin (42) penalty
HOLLAND:
Ageaus Yme (Gejus) van der Meulen - Dolf van Kol, Sjaak de Bruin - Huib de Leeuw, 
Maarten Grobbe, Koos van der Wildt - Cor Kools, Frans Homborg, Wim Tap, Felix Smeets, 
Gep Landaal.

SCOTLAND:
Alexander (Sandy) McLaren            (3/St Johnstone) -
Douglas Herbert Gray                            (4/Rangers)
Joseph Nibloe                                                (3/Kilmarnock) -
Hugh Auld Morton                                                                 (2/Kilmarnock)
Allan Craig                                                                                          (2/Motherwell)
Thomas Craig [c]                                                                                             (5/Rangers) -
James Nisbet                                                                                                                  (3/Ayr United)
Alexander George Cheyne                                                                                                                   (4/Aberdeen)
James William Fleming                                                                                                                           (2/Rangers)
Robert Rankin                                                                                                                                                (3/St Mirren)
Robert Howe                                                                                                                                                              (2/Hamilton Academical)

Notes:  This was an unofficial match for Holland.
        At the match, both national anthems were played and all present in the stadium were 
        under the impression it was an official match, but months later, the NVB (Dutch FA) 
        declared it was not official, a decision taken by NVB president ir. Kips, who was 
        strictly opposed against playing professionals (as the Scots of course were). 



